<DOC><DOCNO> AP900210-0094 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-90 1434EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Turkey-Mine     02-10 0234</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Turkey-Mine,0243</SECOND><HEAD>Mine Officials Ordered Arrested in Connection With Fatal Fire</HEAD><DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Three mining officials were arrested oncharges of criminal negligence Saturday in connection with a mineexplosion and fire that killed 67 men, Turkish news reports said.   The Anatolia news agency identified the three as mine directorHasan Saritepe, chief engineer Cemal Tiryakioglu and safetyengineer Husnu Meydan.   Earlier Saturday, Saritepe and Tiryakioglu were fired from theirposts.   The Anatolia and Hurriyet news agencies said soldiers and policehad to restrain grieving relatives of the victims who tried toattack the men.   The crowd shouted ``Murderers!'' and threw stones at the vantaking them away to the northern city of Merzifon, where thecharges were filed. Each faces four to 10 years in prison ifconvicted.   Fire erupted in the Yeniceltic mine, 240 miles northeast ofAnkara, following a powerful metane gas explosion.   Union officials and relatives of the victims have alleged thatSaritepe was aware of methane gas leakage in the mine but failed toevacuate the pit 316 yards underground.   Officials initially said 58 miners were trapped in the mine. Butthey said Saturday that one more miner missing since Wednesdayevening's explosion was now believed trapped. The missing minerswere presumed dead. The bodies of eight other miners were removedfrom the mine.   Two workers were injured.   The fire was still burning Saturday, Anatolia said.</TEXT></DOC>